{{Infobox ancient site |name = Khirbet El-Knese |native_name = |alternate_name = El-Knese, El Knese |image = |alt = |caption = |map_type = Lebanon |map_alt = |map_size = 200 |location = south of [[Yanta (village)|Yanta]] |region = [[Rashaya District]] |coordinates = {{coord|33.5841|35.9202|display=inline}} |type = |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = |builder = |material = |built = |abandoned = |epochs = |cultures = [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = |archaeologists = |condition = Ruins |ownership = |management = |public_access = Yes |website = |notes = }} '''Khirbet El-Knese''', '''El-Knese''' or '''El Knese''' are two [[Roman temple]]s south of [[Yanta (village)|Yanta]], north of [[Rashaya]] in the [[Rashaya District]] of the [[Beqaa Governorate]] in [[Lebanon]].<ref name="Talbert2000">{{cite book|author=Richard J.A. Talbert|title=Barrington Atlas of the Greek and Roman World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x_FHmc_E2uQC&pg=PA1063|accessdate=19 September 2012|date=18 September 2000|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-04945-8|pages=1063–}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/678242 |title=Places: 678242 (Khirbet el-Knese) |author=Brown, J., E. Meyers, R. Talbert, T. Elliott, S. Gillies |accessdate=September 19, 2012 <!-- 6:30 pm --> |publisher=Pleiades}}</ref><ref name="Taylor1971">{{cite book|author=George Taylor|title=The Roman temples of Lebanon: a pictorial guide. Les temples romains au Liban; guide illustré|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ii8NAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=19 September 2012|year=1971|publisher=Dar el-Machreq Publishers}}</ref><ref name="Keel1997">{{cite book|author=Othmar Keel|title=The Symbolism of the Biblical World: Ancient Near Eastern Iconography and the Book of Psalms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fy4B1iMg33YC&pg=PA159|accessdate=19 September 2012|year=1997|publisher=Eisenbrauns|isbn=978-1-57506-014-9|pages=159–}}</ref>
The upper and lower temples are included in a group of [[Temples of Mount Hermon]]. The lower temple faces east with the peak of [[Mount Hermon]] to the south. George F. Taylor described it as an [[Antae temple]] with moulded [[architrave]]s to the right of the south antae.<ref name="Taylor1971"/> El Knese has supposed connections to the word "[[Ecclesia (ancient Athens)|ecclesia]]".<ref name="WilsonWarren1871">{{cite book|author1=Sir Charles William Wilson|author2=Sir Charles Warren|title=The recovery of Jerusalem: a narrative of exploration and discovery in the city and the Holy Land|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-BIGAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA432|accessdate=19 September 2012|year=1871|publisher=Richard Bentley|pages=432–}}</ref>
